      <div type="translation">
        <head>Translation</head>
        <ab>Not even after death have you lost your fine reputation in the whole earth, but still all the splendid <supplied reason="subaudible">achievements</supplied> of your soul remain - both those which you inherited, and those which you learnt, according to your nature, most excellent in intellect. So now, Pytheas, you have also gone to the Island of the Blest.</ab>
      </div>

      <div type="commentary">
        <head>Commentary</head>
        <p>This epigram, preserved only in the <title>Greek Anthology</title>, was very probably inscribed at Aphrodisias for Pytheas, for whom see <xref type="inscription" n="55" href="110070">11.70</xref>, <xref type="inscription" n="56" href="020020">2.20</xref>, <xref type="inscription" n="57" href="080610">8.610</xref>, <xref type="inscription" n="58" href="050303">5.303</xref>, and discussion at <xref type="eAla-text" n="V.18">V.18</xref>.</p>
        
      </div>

      <div type="history" n="locations"><head>Locations</head><p>Found: <rs type="found">No description.</rs>. Original location: <rs type="origLocation">Unknown.</rs>. Last recorded location: <rs type="lastLocation">No description.</rs>. </p></div>

      

      

      <div type="history" n="record">
        <head>History of Recording</head>
        <p>An epigram either recorded, almost certainly at Aphrodisias, by a Byzantine copyist, or intended for inscription at Aphrodisias; not reported subsequently.</p>
      </div>

